solution.p:
(b) The induced EMF in the ring is equal to the rate of change of flux.

	\mathcal{E} = \left|\dfrac{d\Phi}{dt} \right| = \omega\:B\:A\:\sin\theta(t)

The magnitude of the induced current in the ring is obtained by dividing the induced EMF by the resistance of the ring.

	 I  \amp  = \dfrac{\mathcal{E}}{R} = \dfrac{\omega\:B\:A\:|\sin\theta(t)|}{R}
	 \amp  = \dfrac{2\pi\times 5\:\textrm{Hz}\times 2\times 10^{-4}\:\textrm{T}\times \pi\:(0.1\:\textrm{m})^2}{10\:\Omega} 
	 \amp = 1.97\times 10^{-5}|\sin(10\pi\:t)|\: \textrm{Amp}.
